In general this looks good to me.  Some overly critical comments:  

There is something about basing the decision to replace creds on their current string (hidden_*) that rattles me.  I realize that it will be quite unlikely that the actual creds will meant that string but all the same it would be nice to have that decision made on something more definitive like a 'scrub' field in the DB perhaps (that way other storage modules could take advantage of it).  Or if nothing else perhaps a config option to replace the default string (hidden_*).

Also I am trying to see how this would work with anonymous swift urls.  Either because the operator is dealing with a store that doesn't use a password (perhaps host based authentication) or because an anonymous/temporary swift url was added to the location.  From eye-balling it I think this will be fine but it might be good to have a test for it.

Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@iccha-sethi, I have a critical concern about this change, under the change the sensitive info will be removed from location string from the DB record when store add image and the info will be inserted (by parse_uri()) to location when the store using the location to do something, such as api/repo code call store get(), delete().

so under this design with current you changed, the client side will could not get correct/available location string even admin enable it with 'show_image_direct_url' (or 'show_multiple_locations', incoming) option, api client will always get scrubbed location string. this will caused client such as nova could not consume image by location url directly, it need always need download it from glance. I think this is a /really/ bad idea.

Actually under my plan, nova will could consume image by location directly if there's a. have available 'image handle' and image has particular location url. please refer: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/image-multiple-location (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/33409/2/nova/virt/images.py)

So, IMO, can we give a option to glance to allow admin disable this scrub behavior? or you have other idea about this? thanks.

Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

A few notes:

1) I'm with Stuart--we should still be able to support multiple backend accounts/containers. Unfortunately, I can't think of any way to do this other than requiring a glance configuration like the following:

<id1>: user1, pass1
<id2>: user2, pass2
...

and then running a find/replace on all the swift locations in the db, erroring out if the substitution for a given user/pass combination is not provided in the config. I also don't love reusing the user info part of the httpurl, and would rather we just tack on the credentials id at the end of the url, after a space or some other url-terminating character. AKA, "swift://user1:pass1@authhost.example.com:8770/glance/foo" would become "swift://authhost.example.com:8770/glance/foo id1".


@zhiyan, the explicit purpose of this change is to enable always exposing location data even to less trusted parties. To make this work, nova and glance are going to have to share configuration for determining the actual user credentials, assuming nova wants to talk directly to the store. Is sharing configuration a suitable solution?


Regarding metadata encryption, I think the main thing that is needed is for us to decrypt the location from the database before performing the substitution.

A comment on the approach rather than the code.

If glance is deployed in an automated way (eg chef, puppet) there may be an issue
with this approach with regard to changing the swift backend password. (Though no worse than
the existing code).

Lets imagine you have two glance-api servers and an original password 'p1'.
You wish to change the password to 'p2'. You will not necessarily be able to
synchronize the writing out of the two glance-api.conf files, eg chef may write
the first node's config file at 12:00:00 but the second node's config file some time
later, eg at 12:07:40. In the mean time requests to the second node for old images
will fail. Similarly the synchronization of the password change itself with the config
file change may be problematic for automated deploys.

What would be required for this to work would be two passwords which are 'live' at
the same time. During the deploy both would be active, when the deploy is complete
the old password would be retired. Keystone does not provide this functionality, but
keystone v3 does provide something similar; user access keys:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/keystone/+spec/access-key-authentication

It is possible to have more than one 'live' user access key available at the same point
in time. If glance switched to using 'user access keys' to acquire a token for
swift operations it would be possible to automatically deploy a credential change
(ie move from one access key to a new one).

Should we consider this approach? (Here? In a separate blueprint?)

Patch Set 41:

A couple of thoughts on the current approach.

The current approach uses an 'in-band' method to signify that
the crendentials should be taken from the glance-api.conf file.
What I mean is that we use the existing 'location' format, but with a
special scrub user to signify 'take the credentials from the
config file'.

This approach means that the scrub user credentials are a
sort of 'pseudo' back end credential. If they leak it is possible
to use them (for example by setting the location) to access
other users' images. So, in some sense, the goal of this patch

 > The image locations table stores the swift url for images
 > which includes the user and key values. This if exposed
 > can cause security risk. 

is not achieved. We are still storing a form of credentials
in the database, which if leaked, allows user access to
images.

Also, if the scrub credentials are leaked and you wish to change
the scrub username/password this is a non-trivial task since
all images' metadata must be updated. While the scrub user credential
change is being performed some images would be offline as they would
not yet have been updated to the new scrub user/password. Ideally
all images should remain accessible in the event of any password
change.

A potential alternative 'out-of-band' approach may not have those
undesirable features.

For example, lets assume that swift+https://:/container/image is currently
an invalid location format. We could adopt this format to mean "take the
credentials from file". (The absent username/password and second ':' denotes
that we wish to take the credentials from the glance-api.conf file.)

We can forbid users directly setting the location to that format under
any circumstances. ie using --location to set to that format would
be forbidden. (The API would set an image's location to that format
on behalf of a user for a 'regular' upload.)

This out-of-band approach would mean:

 1) no credentials/pseudo-credentials in the database
 2) no pseudo-password change which would require a metadata update of all images.
 3) no pseudo-credentials to be leaked (which users
    can use nefariously)

Thinking about the multi-store case a bit more it seems that currently we don't really have full support for where
you may want to bring a new backend swift store online. For example I don't this its currently possible if, say, your current store is http and the new one is https, or the current one resides in 'region a' while the new on resides in 'region b'.

It occurred to be that it would be possible to define a new location format as follows:

"store" would denote which backend store we wish to use. We would then define the attributes of that store in the configuration.

Hi Sridevik,

Thanks for your updated patches.

I'd like to return to the issue of https+swift:// versus swift:// ...

First, a reminder that setting a "file://" location is forbidden:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/4602/5/glance/api/v1/images.py

This is to prevent users setting a location to something like "file://etc/passwd" which would allow access arbitrary files on the system. (A security hole).

I previously gave an example of an employee leaving an organisation. In this case, the operator will change the swift backend password to a new value (unknown to the ex-employee), but the 'store' name in the location (swift://<*store*>/<container>/<object>) will remain unchanged. Since the ex-employee still knows the store name he or she can set a new location using the known store name -- this will potentially allow access to any image data. (A security hole).

To prevent users setting 'store' style locations I think we need a way to disambiguate between 'system' set 'store' locations and user set arbitrary swift locations.

Previously I'd suggested using "https+swift://" for user specified locations and "swift://" for new-style system locations which specify a 'store' (using the format swift://<store>/<container>/<object>).

I hadn't reaslised that swift:// was already in use (it means the same thing as https+swift://). I had

Hi Sridevi,

Thanks for your continued heroic work on this patch :-)

I think what we're doing here can benefit multi-tenant stores also.
I don't think it would be fair to ask you to make any code changes per se for
that, but if we changed some of the wording / config options that may make things
clearer in the future.

Let me try to explain where I'm coming from.

Right now (with this patch) we're using "glance-swift.conf" basically to store credentials for the single tenant store. However, in the future we could also use it to fully describe how to instantiate a swift client for any given swift store.

So, in the future we could potentially have something like:

  glance-swift.conf:
  [ref1]
  user = tenant:user1
  key = key1
  auth_url = http://auth123@example.com

  [ref2]
  multi-tenant = True
  swift_url = http://swift.example.com
  insecure = False

  [ref3]
  multi-tenant = True
  swift_url = http://swift2.example.com
  insecure = True
  
In this case we have a single tenant store like we have today (ref1), but also have multi-tenant stores (ref2, ref3), which take advantage of a new 'insecure' swift client option (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/69187). Note neither 'ref2' nor 'ref3' actually contain any credentials.

Do you think it would be ok to re-word some things so that the wording would be less specific to a single tenant store with credentials? Eg "Configuring Multiple Swift Accounts" would change to "Configuring Multiple Swift Stores".

(I'd be happy to pull down the patch and propose something if you'd be ok with that?)
